Money Stuff =0A The first-principles theory of a lot of private investments=
 goes roughly like =0Athis: There are a lot of investment opportunities tha=
t are, fo =0A=0A=0A <> =0A =0A<https://sli.bloomberg.com/click=3Fs=3D825881=
&stpe=3Ddefault&li=3D12236766&m=3D21d6dea82d6b16615cf44233be620525&p=3D0107=
2025>=0A=0A=0A=0APrivate equity in 401(k)s=0A=0AThe first-principles theory=
 of a lot of private investments goes roughly like =0Athis:=0A=0A * There a=
re a lot of investment opportunities that are, for more or less good =0Area=
sons, illiquid. If you invest money in an early-stage startup, you are =0Am=
aking a long-term bet on its success, and you don=E2=80=99t expect to know =
anytime =0Asoon if your bet is right. It would be weird to sell your invest=
ment a week =0Aafter making it, in a way that it would not be weird to buy =
Nvidia stock today =0Aand sell it in a week. If you buy a company in a leve=
raged buyout, it is in =0Apart because you think you can run it better outs=
ide of public markets: You can =0Atake a longer-term view, or run more leve=
