</tr> </table> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first-principles theory of =
a lot of private investments goes roughly like this:</p> <ol style=3D"list-=
style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"> <li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">There are a lot of investment opportunities that are, for=
 more or less good reasons, illiquid. If you invest money in an early-stage=
 startup, you are making a long-term bet on its success, and you don=E2=80=
=99t expect to know anytime soon if your bet is right. It would be weird to=
 sell your investment a week after making it, in a way that it would not be=
 weird to buy Nvidia stock today and sell it in a week. If you buy a compan=
y in a leveraged buyout, it is in part because you think you can run it bet=
ter outside of public markets: You can take a longer-term view, or run more=
 leverage, than public investors want; locking up your money for years is a=
 prerequisite to doing the things that you think will add value. If you mak=
e a direct loan to a company, with a high interest rate and custom-negotiat=
ed structural features, it=E2=80=99s because you expect a long-term relatio=
nship with the company; you can=E2=80=99t just sell the loan the next day.<=
/li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The people making these sorts of ill=
iquid investments will tend to be professionally managed investment funds =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0venture capital, private equity or private credit funds =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0with long lives and no need for immediate liquidity.=C2=A0</li>=
 <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Those funds, in turn, will lock up their=
 investors=E2=80=99 money for a long time, to match their assets (illiquid =
investments) and their liabilities (long-term locked-up investor money).</l=
i> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Therefore, their=C2=A0investors=C2=A0s=
hould be people with a lot of money that they won=E2=80=99t need for a long=
 time. Insurance companies are the most obvious example: If you sell life i=
nsurance polices (or annuities), you will invest the premiums you get, and =
you quite predictably won=E2=80=99t have to pay most of it out for a long t=
ime. So if an investment manager comes to you and says =E2=80=9Cif you inve=
st with me I can give you better returns than the public markets, but I hav=
e to warn you that you can=E2=80=99t get your money back for 10 years,=E2=
=80=9D that=E2=80=99s perfect: You won=E2=80=99t need the money for 10 year=
s, and you like high returns. University endowments and sovereign wealth fu=
nds have similar profiles, and like to invest in private assets.<a href=3D"=
#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: n=
one !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-b=
lock;"> <span>[1]</span> </a> </li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also =
pension funds. If you run a pension for a company, and you put aside $1,000=
 for a 25-year-old starting out at the company, you won=E2=80=99t need that=
 money until she retires in 35 years. So you can get paid for taking some i=
lliquidity. And pension funds are, again, often investors in private assets=
.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Most people in the US don=E2=80=
=99t have pensions, though, these days. Mostly they have defined-contributi=
on retirement plans:=C2=A0<em>They=C2=A0</em>put aside some money every yea=
r, in specially designed accounts, to build their own retirement pension. H=
mm.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also the investment professional=
s who manage these private investment funds tend to charge high fees.</li> =
</ol> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Actually I guess only the first five bul=
let points on that list are part of the first-principles theory of private =
investments. The seventh is not a=C2=A0<em>necessary=C2=A0</em>part of that=
 theory, and you could imagine someone starting a private equity fund and c=
harging very low fees. But it does seem reasonable to expect private invest=
ments to have structurally higher fees than public ones. For one thing, =E2=
=80=9Cbuy all the stocks=E2=80=9D is an approach to public investing that (=
1) compares favorably to many other approaches (like =E2=80=9Cbuy only the =
good stocks=E2=80=9D) and (2) can be done very, very cheaply. So if you lau=
nch a business like =E2=80=9CI will invest in big public stocks and charge =
2% of assets,=E2=80=9D your competitors will charge less for a better produ=
ct and you will not raise a lot of money. Whereas there is probably no simi=
larly simple low-barriers-to-entry way to do private-market investing,<a hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;"> <span>[2]</span> </a>=C2=A0and the actual work of private inv=
esting =E2=80=94=C2=A0finding the right opportunities, doing due diligence =
without public financials, building relationships with companies, getting i=
nvolved in operations, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0just does seem more labor-intens=
ive than picking public stocks. There are a lot of retail hobbyist stock tr=
aders; there are fewer retail hobbyist leveraged buyout sponsors.<a href=3D=
"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;"> <span>[3]</span> </a></p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the six=
th bullet point is the interesting one. If your basic theory is =E2=80=9Cpr=
ivate investments should be held by people who predictably won=E2=80=99t ne=
ed their money back for years (because they are the sensible bearers of ill=
iquidity risk), and conversely people who predictably won=E2=80=99t need th=
eir money back for years should buy private investments (because they offer=
 higher returns than liquid public investments),=E2=80=9D then it is honest=
ly sort of weird to mess around with relatively niche categories like =E2=
=80=9Cuniversity endowments=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CUS public pension funds=E2=
=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cannuity providers.=E2=80=9D The overwhelmingly gigantic=
=C2=A0obvious category is=C2=A0retirement savers. If you=C2=A0are yourself =
a 25-year-old putting aside $1,000 for your retirement, in a tax-advantaged=
 account that more or less doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0allow=C2=A0you to take the =
money out for 35 years,<a href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;"> <span>[4]</span> </a> then you ar=
e a pretty safe source of capital for long-term illiquid investments. And i=
f those investments offer a higher return than public markets =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0because they pay for that illiquidity =E2=80=94=C2=A0then they are good =
for you too.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then if they charge more =
than all of that extra return in fees, they are bad for you. But good for t=
he people charging the fees.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway it=E2=
=80=99s hard to get a lot of venture capital, private equity or even privat=
